04986nam a22008175i 9780823262441DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232624417 a10.1515/97808232624412doi  a(DE-B1597)555387  a(OCoLC)889302779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJK1853b.D558 2014 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aDilts, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPunishment and Inclusion :bRace, Membership, and the Limits of American Liberalism /cAndrew Dilts. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJust Ideas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note About the Cover -- t1. A Productive Injustice -- t2. Fabricating Figures -- t3. Neoliberal Penality and the Biopolitics of Homo CEconomicus -- t4. To Kill a Thief -- t5. Innocent Citizens, Guilty Subjects -- t6. Punishing at the Ballot Box -- t7. Civic Disabilities -- t8. (Re)figuring Justice -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the start of the twenty-first century, 1 percent of the U.S. population is behind bars. An additional 3 percent is on parole or probation. In all but two states, incarcerated felons cannot vote, and in three states felon disenfranchisement is for life. More than 5 million adult Americans cannot vote because of a felony-class criminal conviction, meaning that more than 2 percent of otherwise eligible voters are stripped of their political rights. Nationally, fully a third of the disenfranchised are African American, effectively disenfranchising 8 percent of all African Americans in the United States. In Alabama, Kentucky, and Florida, one in every five adult African Americans cannot vote.Punishment and Inclusion gives a theoretical and historical account of this pernicious practice of felon disenfranchisement, drawing widely on early modern political philosophy, continental and postcolonial political thought, critical race theory, feminist philosophy, disability theory, critical legal studies, and archival research into state constitutional conventions. It demonstrates that the history of felon disenfranchisement, rooted in postslavery restrictions on suffrage and the contemporaneous emergence of the modern "American" penal system, reveals the deep connections between two political institutions often thought to be separate, showing the work of membership done by the criminal punishment system and the work of punishment done by the electoral franchise.Felon disenfranchisement is a symptom of the tension that persists in democratic politics between membership and punishment. This book shows how this tension is managed via the persistence of white supremacy in contemporary regimes of punishment and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPolitical rights, Loss ofzUnited States. 0aPrisonersxSuffragezUnited States. 0aSuffragezUnited States. 0aSuffrage--United States. 4aCivil Death. 4aFelon Disenfranchisement. 4aJohn Locke. 4aLiberalism. 4aMaryland. 4aMichel Foucault. 4aPunishment. 4aVoting Rights. 4ainclusion. 4apolitical membership. 4arace. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823262441zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823262441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823262441.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_S